 the world during the past twenty years. A profile of the former chef to Kim Jong Il of North Korea describes Kim’s exacting standards for gourmet fare, which he gorges himself on while his country starves. A journalist becomes part of the inner circle of an IRA cell thanks to his drinking buddies. And a young, inexperienced female journalist shares mud crab in a foxhole with an equally young Hamid Karzai. Along with tales of deprivation and repression are stories of generosity and pleasure, sometimes overlapping. This memorable collection, introduced and edited by Matt McAllester, is seasoned by tragedy and violence, spiced with humor and good will, and fortified, in McAllester’s words, with "a little more humanity than we can usually slip into our newspapers and magazine stories."  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aFood habitsvAnecdotes. 0aFood habitsxAnecdotes. 0aForeign correspondentsvAnecdotes. 0aForeign journalistsvAnecdotes. 0aForeign journalistsxAnecdotes. 0aSurvival and emergency rationsvAnecdotes. 0aSurvival and emergency rationsxAnecdotes. 0aWar and societyvAnecdotes. 0aWar and societyxAnecdotes. 0aWar correspondentsvAnecdotes. 0aWar correspondentsxAnecdotes. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Agriculture & Food (see also POLITICAL SCIENCE / Public Policy / Agriculture & Food Policy).2bisacsh1 aAnderson, Jon Lee, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAnderson, Scott, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBurke, Jason, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChandrasekaran, Rajiv, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDemick, Barbara, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFassihi, Farnaz, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/